04883nam a22006495i 9780292795914DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212006txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927959147 a10.7560/7129592doi  a(DE-B1597)586962  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aNX587.75.A1bB43 2006eb 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a704/.04209642221 aBecker, Cynthia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmazigh Arts in Morocco :bWomen Shaping Berber Identity /cCynthia Becker. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2006  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tA Note on Transcription and Transliteration -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne. Ait Khabbash Textiles:Weaving Metaphors of Identity -- tTwo. The Art of Dressing the Body -- tThree. Dance Performances: Negotiating Gender and Social Change -- tFour. Women as Public Symbols of Identity: The Adornment of the Bride and Groom -- tFive. Performing Amazigh Gender Roles:Wedding Ceremonies -- tSix. Oh, My Sudanese Mother: The Legacy of Slavery in Ait Khabbash Art -- tSeven. Contemporary Amazigh Arts: Giving Material Form to Amazigh Consciousness -- tAppendix. Selected Songs from Ait KhabbashWeddings -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn southeastern Morocco, around the oasis of Tafilalet, the Ait Khabbash people weave brightly colored carpets, embroider indigo head coverings, paint their faces with saffron, and wear ornate jewelry. Their extraordinarily detailed arts are rich in cultural symbolism; they are always breathtakingly beautiful—and they are typically made by women. Like other Amazigh (Berber) groups (but in contrast to the Arab societies of North Africa), the Ait Khabbash have entrusted their artistic responsibilities to women. Cynthia Becker spent years in Morocco living among these women and, through family connections and female fellowship, achieved unprecedented access to the artistic rituals of the Ait Khabbash. The result is more than a stunning examination of the arts themselves, it is also an illumination of women's roles in Islamic North Africa and the many ways in which women negotiate complex social and religious issues. One of the reasons Amazigh women are artists is that the arts are expressions of ethnic identity, and it follows that the guardians of Amazigh identity ought to be those who literally ensure its continuation from generation to generation, the Amazigh women. Not surprisingly, the arts are visual expressions of womanhood, and fertility symbols are prevalent. Controlling the visual symbols of Amazigh identity has given these women power and prestige. Their clothing, tattoos, and jewelry are public identity statements; such public artistic expressions contrast with the stereotype that women in the Islamic world are secluded and veiled. But their role as public identity symbols can also be restrictive, and history (French colonialism, the subsequent rise of an Arab-dominated government in Morocco, and the recent emergence of a transnational Berber movement) has forced Ait Khabbash women to adapt their arts as their people adapt to the contemporary world. By framing Amazigh arts with historical and cultural context, Cynthia Becker allows the reader to see the full measure of these fascinating artworks.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aArts, BerberzMorocco. 0aBerberszMoroccoxSocial life and customs. 0aEthnicity in art. 0aIdentity (Psychology) in art. 0aWomen artistszMorocco. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292795914423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cove